        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": ">Why not use actual tabs for that?\r\n\r\nBecause they don't really make sense for that.\r\n\r\nhttps://stackoverflow.com/questions/26708822/why-do-vim-experts-prefer-buffers-over-tabs\r\nhttp://joshldavis.com/2014/04/05/vim-tab-madness-buffers-vs-tabs/\r\n\r\n>No need to memorize buffer numbers, :buffer accepts partial names. E.g. :b foo switches to /blah/foo.txt.\r\n\r\nYeah I do use that. However I rarely find I need more than five or six open buffers, so It's still quicker to just use <kbd>Tab</kbd> and <kbd>Shift</kbd><kbd>Tab</kbd> (`:bn` and `:bp`) to switch between them, and <kbd>Leader</kbd><kbd>d</kbd> to delete (`:bd`), so being able to reorder would be nice.\r\n\r\n>>I know some plugins get around this by implementing their own virtual buffer list\r\n\r\n>The buffer list is just a list. The fact that :ls shows them one way doesn't mean you can't list them another way, with a plugin.\r\n\r\nYeah, as I said I know you can implement your own list, but as this is the only case in which you can't just use the built-in one it seemed worth asking whether changing the order was possible.\r\n\r\n>Buffer numbers are ids, they cannot and must not be changed.\r\n\r\nOkay, sounds pretty conclusive, thanks.",
